<br>
Now how in the world do you rest in a persistant world?  If a spellcaster needs to get spells back, then they would have to rest for 8 hours, so are they down for 8 hours? Obviously I highly doubt that or no one will be a spellcaster.  Another option would be to have everyone automatically rest, but again this would not be practical because one party could be killing a dragon when a lowly level 1 mage wants his magic missle back.<br>
<br>
So my guess is that spellcasting will be handled the exact same way as every other MMORPG, they will have mana or power.  This is gained back slowly and spellcasting depletes it.  Is this the way it will be done?<br>
<br>
-Uladar <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#97694F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub26.ezboard.com/udeevadeelight.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Deeva Deelight</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NWN PlayTester</span><br>  Posts: 192<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(1/22/02 6:34:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub26.ezboard.com/fapex71990frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=191.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How does NWN handle spells &amp; spellcasting?</span><hr size=1> No mana, for all spell casting classes other than sorcerers and bards, spells will be traditional D&amp;D memorization.  However, with the reality of players not wanting to sit around and 'sleep' for 8 hours for the casters to get spells, it has been slightly modified.  They will allow relearning of spells as characters 'rest.'  The amount of rest necessary, or the real amount of time that will take, has not been disclosed as far as i know.  However, the designers have mentioned that they are making it very beenficial for the entire party to periodically rest while not making it too cumbersome on the players.<br>
<br>
Therefore, hopefully they struck a nice balance with memorization = meditating while at the same time maintaining their tradition of making spell casters make the tough decisions of predicting which spells will be beneficial for the upcoming encounters.  This will allow the game to continue moving smoothly without allowing spell casters to see an encounter, back off and then memorize the spells they think are best on the fly. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#97694F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub26.ezboard.com/usegalsoulsaver.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Segal SoulSaver</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://wwp.icq.com/scripts/online.dll?icq=112539253&img=5" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lead-GM</span><br>  Posts: 2589<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(1/22/02 9:30:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub26.ezboard.com/fapex71990frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=191.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How does NWN handle spells &amp; spellcasting?</span><hr size=1> I think Deeva summed up what we know so far.  They plan on tuning that during the Beta to creat a system where each player is allowed a number of rests periods per day to acquire some of their lost powers.   Each individual 'rests' independent of other players.  <br>
<br>
Unlike games like BG and BG2, there is no global pause function except for use by the GM.   All actions take place in real time on a 6 second clock, though you can Queue your actions if you wanted too. <p><b>Segal SoulSaver</b><br>
